---
import React from "../components/counters/React";
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<html lang="en">
	<BaseLayout title="ðŸš€">
		<h1 class="text-6xl font-bold text-secondary">Enter Astro!</h1>
		<h2 class="text-2xl">
			Astro is a framework that uses the <span class="text-secondary"
				>Island Architecture</span
			>
		</h2>
		<h3 class="text-2xl">
			By default, the server renders HTML, and sends just that back to the
			client. Any interactivity requires you to <span
				class="text-secondary">opt in</span
			>. These sections where you opt in are called <div
				class="text-secondary animate-bounce"
			>
				interactive islands.
			</div>
		</h3>

		<p>
			For example... the counter on the left and the counter on the right
			both use the same component. The one on the right uses the
			"client:load" directive to opt in to client rendering.
		</p>

		<div class="flex flex-row flex-wrap gap-8">
			<React />
			<React client:load />
		</div>
	</BaseLayout>
</html>
